AB  - Maroons originate from armed self-emancipation against enslavement in the Americas, with Jamaica hosting Maroon communities now organized as ethnoculturally distinct polities. Maroon ethnogenesis and struggle gave rise to an environmental ethos in which the features of local ecosystems are deeply intertwined with collective historical memory and spiritual life. The Accompong Maroons of Jamaica harness within their social order a distinct approach to environmental protection grounded in ancestral connections to the land, described here as Maroon Ecology. This ethos drives their struggle against extractive industry, the actions of which the Maroons find detrimental to the integrity of their land and autonomy. The praxis of Maroon Ecology locates Maroon struggle within the global environmental justice movement, diverging from dominant Jamaican environmentalism by demanding sovereignty and territorial redistribution as a part of environmental protection. This latest iteration of Accompong's legacy of resistance positions the Maroons as key actors in Caribbean environmental and development politics.
