AB  - It has often been said that 'fairness lies in the eye of the beholder'. Contrary to decision criteria such as economic efficiency, the notion of fairness or equity cannot be given a definition independent from context. Economists have thus long shied away from including concerns about justice in their policy recommendations. Here we take context-dependence as a starting point and turn it into an advantage. We first establish that it is not random but highly structured by both social position-dependent and non-positional dimensions of context, and these can also interact in specific ways. We use laboratory experiments to explore the role of wealth and need (in the form of 'mouths to feed') and that of real financial incentives, veil-of-ignorance and equity-efficiency trade-offs. We also find that the very definition of equity norms is context-dependent in terms of implicit parameters and sub-rules. Insights from these results led to the construction of an 'equity metric' that is able to represent a collective's heterogeneous equity preferences that minimise total 'perceived inequity'. Although it has some inherent limitations, our metric increases the likelihood for equity and a competing policy goal to correlate positively, thereby reducing tensions and allowing higher achievements of both.
